{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6e07f2ad-ab44-457c-a7cb-34c0e6e6f0c0","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_011GG7NFgtRFSG5KFSsa2RN1","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Fixing MSTest v4 compatibility"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01FXqTkCLMen7fXTx2C4SPS5","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"cd /tmp/sv-a3aaacc2ac09491589c92290f01db3a4 && dotnet restore --verbosity quiet 2>&1 | tail -5 && dotnet build --no-restore 2>&1 | tail -15","description":"Build with current MSTest v3 to verify baseline","initial_wait":30},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Build with current MSTest v3 to verify baseline"}],"interactionId":"503833e0-42c3-4af2-88b2-a720f931feac","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user says they're upgrading to MSTest v4, but the project currently references MSTest 3.8.0. In MSTest v4, the `TestMethodAttribute` constructor signature changed - the parameterless constructor was removed or changed, and the constructor now requires a `string? displayName` parameter.\n\nLet me check what the MSTest v4 change looks like. In MSTest v4, `TestMethodAttribute` no longer has a parameterless constructor - instead it has a constructor that takes `string? displayName = null`. So when you have a subclass like `CategorizedTestMethodAttribute` that doesn't pass a display name to the base constructor, it would fail because there's no parameterless base constructor.\n\n\nThe issue is that the subclass constructor implicitly calls the parameterless base constructor, which no longer exists in v4. To fix this, I need to update the package to MSTest v4 and then either pass a display name to the base constructor or explicitly call `base(null)` to use the new signature.","outputTokens":540,"requestId":"A041:243205:1C3FD66:2054F3A:69FEA3AB"},"id":"7235cae0-b7ae-4968-a140-43a6ed493215","timestamp":"2026-05-09T03:02:33.284Z","parentId":"999899fb-efb4-43d0-b46b-9be2239e69d6"}
